e meaningful coverage seems to rely on dynamic access based on Java code. This artifact lacks classes, and resource tests are already maximized. While adding Google Closure Library may provide resources and classes, it might not significantly enhance coverage. I need to inspect the artifact and its dependencies to be sure about the classes and resource names.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining older versions of dependencies**\\n\\nFor older versions, I see that there are base.js and deps.js files within the third-party library, not just core. It’s interesting that the older third-party jar includes goog/base.js and deps.js, which offer additional support. While it requires core namespaces, it’s not fully packaged — lacking files like array, asserts, or debug. If I plan to run JS tests, I would need core, but the existing tests seem to effectively check the source.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"action\": \"no_action\",\n  \"summary\": \"No extra setup is needed: the artifact has no Java classes, no declared dependencies, and consists of packaged Closure Library third-party JavaScript/resources that can be covered by classpath resource tests.\",\n  \"deterministic_setup\": [],\n  \"agent_guidance\": \"\",\n  \"risks\": [\n    \"The failing existing tests appear version-skewed: 0.0-1376 has older resource names/content such as README instead of README.md and CancelledError instead of CanceledError.\",\n    \"Because the artifact is resource-only JavaScript, meaningful Java reachability coverage is inherently limited to verifying packaged resources and source-level integration points.\"\n  ]\n}", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0bf789b12e9b59d3016a3e5d17180481958decc8bd8fe6b47f\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 22637, "output": 998, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 23635, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrit